00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:16.110 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: No, this is not
Heisenberg from "Breaking Bad."

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:20.910 align:middle line:84%
And not a giant balloon either,
which some people confuse that.

00:05:20.910 --> 00:05:24.930 align:middle line:84%
But the interpretation of
quantum mechanics that's become

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:25.870 align:middle line:90%
very popular--

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:27.690 align:middle line:90%
which I actually disagree with.

00:05:27.690 --> 00:05:29.640 align:middle line:90%
And I can explain that later--

00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:33.630 align:middle line:84%
is the idea that something
is either a particle

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:35.160 align:middle line:90%
or it's a wave.

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:37.330 align:middle line:90%
And we don't know which it is.

00:05:37.330 --> 00:05:40.830 align:middle line:84%
And at some point, it's going to
collapse into one or the other.

00:05:40.830 --> 00:05:43.390 align:middle line:10%
This guy Schrodinger
did this whole--

00:05:43.390 --> 00:05:44.190 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: The cat.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:46.170 align:middle line:10%
>>APOLLO: --thought
experiment with the cat.

00:05:46.170 --> 00:05:48.240 align:middle line:84%
And the cat's either
alive or dead.

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:50.730 align:middle line:84%
And then he makes
up this experiment

00:05:50.730 --> 00:05:54.270 align:middle line:84%
to show that this
interpretation is ridiculous.

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:55.380 align:middle line:90%
He thought it was crazy.

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:55.780 align:middle line:90%
So did Einstein.

00:05:55.780 --> 00:05:57.170 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Schrodinger's cat.

00:05:57.170 --> 00:05:58.920 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: And yet, we
use it all the time.

00:05:58.920 --> 00:05:59.940 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: As an example.

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:04.110 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: And but
popularly, the idea

00:06:04.110 --> 00:06:07.770 align:middle line:84%
