Your wife is old.

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:22.270 align:middle line:90%
It's a bummer.

00:39:22.270 --> 00:39:22.510 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:39:22.510 --> 00:39:23.350 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's a big bummer.

00:39:23.350 --> 00:39:24.517 align:middle line:90%
>>APOLLO: It's a big bummer.

00:39:24.517 --> 00:39:25.520 align:middle line:90%
You don't want to do it.

00:39:25.520 --> 00:39:26.870 align:middle line:90%
It's not a good idea.

00:39:26.870 --> 00:39:31.000 align:middle line:84%
So instead of accelerating, if
you're not warping spacetime

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:34.800 align:middle line:84%
then time is consistent
across your travel.

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:37.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Could you come
back and people are younger

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:39.340 align:middle line:90%
than when you left?

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:42.160 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: Ah, there are some
theoretical approaches to this.

00:39:42.160 --> 00:39:45.160 align:middle line:90%
But again, that still--

00:39:45.160 --> 00:39:49.240 align:middle line:84%
that time dilation, both going
into the future, so to speak--

00:39:49.240 --> 00:39:51.970 align:middle line:84%
if I go and come back and
20 years have passed--

00:39:51.970 --> 00:39:56.230 align:middle line:84%
or going and coming back before
I left, going into the past,

00:39:56.230 --> 00:39:59.510 align:middle line:84%
is still based on this
warp of space time.

00:39:59.510 --> 00:40:02.560 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a vehicle
that's able to move

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:06.220 align:middle line:84%
without acceleration and
jump through space time,

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:07.930 align:middle line:84%
you don't have
that effect either.

00:40:07.930 --> 00:40:10.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What is it about
physics that excites you?

00:40:10.870 --> 00:40:13.540 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: I think that
we have the potential

00:40:13.540 --> 00:40:18.010 align:middle line:84%
to become a species that is
responsible for our planet,

00:40:18.010 --> 00:40:20.890 align:middle line:84%
that is in a
symbiotic relationship

00:40:20.890 --> 00:40:24.490 align:middle line:84%
with our biosphere, and
that has the capacity

00:40:24.490 --> 00:40:27.730 align:middle line:84%
to travel the universe
and interact with beings

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:29.560 align:middle line:90%
all over the galaxy.

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:35.080 align:middle line:84%
I believe that we have
the opportunity right now

00:40:35.080 --> 00:40:40.000 align:middle line:84%
to make a transition to
becoming a galactic species

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:44.650 align:middle line:84%
and to developing a new kind of
relationship and understanding

00:40:44.650 --> 00:40:48.580 align:middle line:84%
with ourselves, with all life
and the rest of the universe.

00:40:48.580 --> 00:40:51.400 align:middle line:84%
And physics paves the
way for us to get there.

00:40:51.400 --> 00:40:53.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, that's
pretty profound

00:40:53.050 --> 00:40:55.360 align:middle line:84%
to be able to say
that like that.

00:40:55.360 --> 00:41:00.490 align:middle line:84%
How do we use that in our day to
day life to make things better?

00:41:00.490 --> 00:41:04.870 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: I think cultivating
our internal physics is needed

00:41:04.870 --> 00:41:06.730 align:middle line:90%
to make changes in our lives.

00:41:06.730 --> 00:41:10.060 align:middle line:84%
Getting to know the root
chakra and its relationship

00:41:10.060 --> 00:41:12.460 align:middle line:84%
to the pentagram and
the sacral chakra

00:41:12.460 --> 00:41:14.920 align:middle line:84%
and its relationship to the
hexagram Nassim was talking

00:41:14.920 --> 00:41:19.270 align:middle line:84%
about, the solar plexus and its
relationship to the heptagram.

00:41:19.270 --> 00:41:23.020 align:middle line:84%
Understanding the geometry
of space in the way

00:41:23.020 --> 00:41:26.470 align:middle line:84%
that it's processed by
our bodies is crucial.

00:41:26.470 --> 00:41:28.000 align:middle line:90%
Because this is your vehicle.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:29.080 align:middle line:90%
This is your spaceship.

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:29.740 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: This is it.

00:41:29.740 --> 00:41:31.690 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: And you're in
it until you leave it.

00:41:31.690 --> 00:41:32.607 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Make it work.

00:41:32.607 --> 00:41:35.290 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: So learning how
to master our capacity

00:41:35.290 --> 00:41:38.578 align:middle line:84%
to use our own energetic
field and develop a deeper

00:41:38.578 --> 00:41:40.370 align:middle line:84%
relationship with
spacetime is fundamental.

00:41:40.370 --> 00:41:42.912 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Adam, did the ancients
understand this, in some way?

00:41:42.912 --> 00:41:45.440 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: I believe that
many ancient cultures did.

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:47.860 align:middle line:84%
And they had
different perspectives

00:41:47.860 --> 00:41:50.360 align:middle line:90%
on the same fundamental truths.

00:41:50.360 --> 00:41:54.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What would you tell a
physicist of the next 20 years

00:41:54.490 --> 00:41:56.620 align:middle line:84%
about what you're
talking about today?

00:41:56.620 --> 00:42:01.440 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: I would say,
let go of the complexities

00:42:01.440 --> 00:42:04.300 align:middle line:84%
of the standard model
of quantum mechanics.

00:42:04.300 --> 00:42:06.060 align:middle line:90%
It's missing so many pieces.

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:10.980 align:middle line:84%
And it's gotten so convoluted
in its mathematical structures.

00:42:10.980 --> 00:42:14.430 align:middle line:84%
It's keeping you from seeing
the simple truths about reality.

00:42:14.430 --> 00:42:15.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is it faulty?

00:42:15.570 --> 00:42:16.830 align:middle line:90%
>>APOLLO: It's very faulty.

00:42:16.830 --> 00:42:20.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yet, no physicists,
other than people like you,

00:42:20.580 --> 00:42:24.360 align:middle line:84%
are coming forward or have
the guts to come forward

00:42:24.360 --> 00:42:25.450 align:middle line:90%
to say that it's faulty.

00:42:25.450 --> 00:42:26.250 align:middle line:90%
Why not?

00:42:26.250 --> 00:42:28.620 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: Well, there
are quite a few of us.

00:42:28.620 --> 00:42:32.160 align:middle line:84%
But when you think about
the structure of funding

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:34.650 align:middle line:84%
in the academic world,
and you look at the fact,

00:42:34.650 --> 00:42:37.770 align:middle line:84%
also, that you have
professors and books.

00:42:37.770 --> 00:42:39.480 align:middle line:84%
And they've been
teaching the same thing

00:42:39.480 --> 00:42:42.090 align:middle line:90%
for the past 15 or 20 years.

00:42:42.090 --> 00:42:44.283 align:middle line:84%
And they want to make
their next tenure.

00:42:44.283 --> 00:42:46.200 align:middle line:84%
And if suddenly there's
all this new physics--

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:46.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And they don't
want to rock the boat.

00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:48.930 align:middle line:10%
>>APOLLO: --and they
don't understand it, yeah,

00:42:48.930 --> 00:42:51.630 align:middle line:10%
they can't-- if they can't
publish something that meets

00:42:51.630 --> 00:42:52.890 align:middle line:10%
the new physics, guess what?

00:42:52.890 --> 00:42:54.270 align:middle line:10%
They lose their tenure.

00:42:54.270 --> 00:42:57.390 align:middle line:10%
Or if you're CERN, and you're
getting $10 billion a year

00:42:57.390 --> 00:42:59.850 align:middle line:10%
to find the Higgs
boson, and someone says,

00:42:59.850 --> 00:43:01.620 align:middle line:10%
actually, you don't
need the Higgs boson

00:43:01.620 --> 00:43:03.287 align:middle line:10%
because spacetime
gives rise to forces--

00:43:03.287 --> 00:43:05.430 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: But let's
keep looking for it.

00:43:05.430 --> 00:43:07.960 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: --then that's $10
billion you're going to lose.

00:43:07.960 --> 00:43:10.620 align:middle line:84%
So there's, I think,
momentum keeping people

00:43:10.620 --> 00:43:12.180 align:middle line:90%
from doing those deeper dives.

00:43:12.180 --> 00:43:13.570 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Adam, thanks for
being on "Beyond Belief."

00:43:13.570 --> 00:43:15.000 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: It's such
a pleasure, George.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:15.875 align:middle line:90%
Thanks for having me.

00:43:15.875 --> 00:43:17.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You're a rebel
physicist, you know that.

00:43:17.940 --> 00:43:19.315 align:middle line:84%
>>APOLLO: I enjoy
that very much.

00:43:19.315 --> 00:43:20.115 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:43:20.115 --> 00:43:22.140 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And it's fun
talking physics with you.

00:43:22.140 --> 00:43:22.470 align:middle line:90%
>>APOLLO: Thank you.

